It&#39;s an opinion - I don&#39;t have=
 any carefully gathered empirical evidence to back it up. However both WCF =
and JAX-RS avoid hypermedia which is pretty important for RESTful solutions=
. In other bits of that email, I pointed out that some JAX-RS compliant fra=
meworks (e.g. Jersey) are now experimenting with hypermedia which makes the=
m much more useful if the abstractions come out right.

In terms of technic=
al critique, I think JAX-RS comes out ahead of WCF because it&#39;s marginally =
easier to TDD with it, and so much more of the framework is above the water=
line rather than buried down deep. However at this point both frameworks ar=
e simply nicer programmatic interfaces atop a Web server, and both short-ch=
ange client-side developers (with JAX-RS again being better than WCF).

Sin=
ce neither has hypermedia support from the start, retrofitting it at this p=
oint may result in horrid abstractions. That&#39;s why I&#39;m broadly supportive o=
f Glenn&#39;s outreach and very supportive of the people behind Restfulie (as w=
ell as being encouraged by the steps the Jersey team are taking).

Jim




